definitions.definition: A combination of events which have come together by chance to make a surprisingly good or wonderful outcome.
An unsought, unintended, and/or unexpected, but fortunate, discovery and/or learning experience that happens by accident.
The mental ability to recover quickly from depression, illness or misfortune.
The physical property of material that can resume its shape after being stretched or deformed; elasticity.

The positive capacity of an organizational system or company to adapt and return to equilibrium due to the consequences of a crisis or failure caused by any type of disruption, including: an outage, natural disasters, man-made disasters, terrorism, or similar (particularly IT systems, archives).
Something which lasts for a short period of time.
Lasting for a short period of time.
Existing for only one day, as with some flowers, insects, and diseases.
(of a body of water) Usually dry, but filling with water for brief periods during and after precipitation.
Lasting for only a moment.
Happening at every moment; perpetual.
Ephemeral or relatively short-lived.
To float.
To pass over rapidly; to skim the surface of.
definitions.example: a ship that fleets the gulf

definitions.definition: To hasten over; to cause to pass away lightly, or in mirth and joy.
To flee, to escape, to speed away.
To evanesce, disappear, die out.
To move up a rope, so as to haul to more advantage; especially to draw apart the blocks of a tackle.
(of people) To move or change in position.
To shift the position of dead-eyes when the shrouds are become too long.
To cause to slip down the barrel of a capstan or windlass, as a rope or chain.
To take the cream from; to skim.
Passing quickly; of short duration.

examples: a ship that fleets the gulf

definitions.definition: Something that happens to someone by chance, a chance occurrence, especially a favourable one.
definitions.example: Gilbert had some bad luck yesterday — he got pick-pocketed and lost fifty dollars.

definitions.definition: A superstitious feeling that brings fortune or success.
definitions.example: He blew on the dice for luck.

definitions.definition: Success.
definitions.example: He has a lot of luck with the ladies, perhaps it is because of his new motorbike.

definitions.definition: The results of a random number generator.
definitions.example: The creators of tool-assisted speedruns often manipulate a lot of luck to get the most favorable results in order to save the most time.

definitions.definition: To succeed by chance.
definitions.example: His plan lucked out.

definitions.definition: To rely on luck.
definitions.example: No plan. We're just to going to have to luck through.

definitions.definition: To carry out relying on luck.
definitions.example: Our plan is to luck it through.

definitions.definition: Expressing distance or motion.
Expressing separation.
Expressing origin.
Expressing agency.
Expressing composition, substance.
Introducing subject matter.
Having partitive effect.
Expressing possession.
Forming the "objective genitive".
Expressing qualities or characteristics.
Expressing a point in time.

That which swallows; the gullet.

definitions.definition: A large deposit of ore in a lode.
A difference, especially a large difference, between groups.
(Oxbridge slang) The bottom part of a list of those awarded a degree, for those who have only just passed.
(Oxbridge slang) To award a degree to somebody who has only just passed sufficiently.

definitions.definition: A negating expression; an answer that shows disagreement or disapproval
A vote not in favor, or opposing a proposition
definitions.example: The workers voted on whether to strike, and there were thirty "yeses" and two "nos".

definitions.definition: (now only used with different, with comparatives more and less, and informally with certain other adjectives such as good and fun) Not, not at all.
definitions.example: I just want to find out whether she's coming or no. (Scotland)

definitions.definition: Without
Like

definitions.definition: Something being indicated that is there; one of those.
(degree) To a given extent or degree.
definitions.example: "The ribbon was that thin." "I disagree, I say it was not that thin, it was thicker... or maybe thinner..."

definitions.definition: (degree) To a great extent or degree; very, particularly (in negative constructions).
definitions.example: I did the run last year, and it wasn't that difficult.

definitions.definition: To such an extent; so. (in positive constructions).
definitions.example: Ooh, I was that happy I nearly kissed her.

definitions.definition: (demonstrative) The thing, person, idea, quality, event, action or time indicated or understood from context, especially if more remote geographically, temporally or mentally than one designated as "this", or if expressing distinction.
definitions.example: He went home, and after that I never saw him again.

definitions.definition: The known (thing); used to refer to something just said.
definitions.example: They're getting divorced. What do you think about that?

definitions.definition: (demonstrative) The aforementioned quality or proposition; used to emphatically affirm or deny a previous statement or question.
definitions.example: The water is so cold! — That it is.

definitions.definition: (relative) (plural that) Which, who; representing a subject, direct object, indirect object, or object of a preposition.
definitions.example: The CPR course that she took really came in handy.

definitions.definition: Used in place of relative adverbs such as where or when; often omitted.
definitions.example: the last time that [= when] I went to Europe

definitions.definition: Introducing a clause which is the subject or object of a verb (such as one involving reported speech), or which is a complement to a previous statement.
definitions.example: He told me that the book is a good read.

definitions.definition: Introducing a subordinate clause expressing a reason or cause: because, in that.
definitions.example: Be glad that you have enough to eat.

definitions.definition: Introducing a subordinate clause that expresses an aim, purpose or goal ("final"), and usually contains the auxiliaries may, might or should: so, so that.
Introducing — especially, but not exclusively, with an antecedent like so or such — a subordinate clause expressing a result, consequence or effect.
definitions.example: The noise was so loud that she woke up.

definitions.definition: Introducing a premise or supposition for consideration: seeing as; inasmuch as; given that; as would appear from the fact that.
Introducing a subordinate clause modifying an adverb.
definitions.example: How often did she visit him? — Twice that I saw.

definitions.definition: Introducing an exclamation expressing a desire or wish.
definitions.example: Oh that spring would come!

definitions.definition: Introducing an exclamation expressing a strong emotion such as sadness or surprise.

definitions.definition: n	Initialism of field Of research.
Pleasing, encouraging or approving.
definitions.example: The candidate wearing the business suite made a favourable impression.

definitions.definition: Useful or helpful.
definitions.example: We made quick progress, due to favourable winds.

definitions.definition: Convenient or at a suitable time; opportune.
definitions.example: The rain stopped at a favourable time for our tennis match.

definitions.definition: Auspicious or lucky.
definitions.example: She says that she was born under a favourable star.

examples: The candidate wearing the business suite made a favourable impression.
We made quick progress, due to favourable winds.
The rain stopped at a favourable time for our tennis match.
She says that she was born under a favourable star.

definitions.definition: With a comparative or with more and a verb phrase, establishes a correlation with one or more other such comparatives.
definitions.example: It looks weaker and weaker, the more I think about it.

definitions.definition: With a comparative, and often with for it, indicates a result more like said comparative. This can be negated with none. See none the.
definitions.example: I'm much the wiser for having had a difficult time like that.

examples: It looks weaker and weaker, the more I think about it.
I'm much the wiser for having had a difficult time like that.

definitions.definition: Offspring.
Lineage.
A difficult return or block of a shot.
Something gained; an acquisition.
(ditransitive) To obtain; to acquire.
definitions.example: I'm going to get a computer tomorrow from the discount store.

definitions.definition: To receive.
definitions.example: He got a severe reprimand for that.

definitions.definition: (in a perfect construction, with present-tense meaning) To have. See usage notes.
definitions.example: I've got a concert ticket for you.

definitions.definition: To fetch, bring, take.
definitions.example: Can you get my bag from the living-room, please?

definitions.definition: To become, or cause oneself to become.
definitions.example: I'm getting hungry; how about you?

definitions.definition: To cause to become; to bring about.
definitions.example: I can't get these boots off (or on).

definitions.definition: To cause to do.
definitions.example: I can't get it to work.

definitions.definition: To cause to come or go or move.
definitions.example: I got him to his room.

definitions.definition: To cause to be in a certain status or position.
definitions.example: Get him here at once.

definitions.definition: (with various prepositions, such as into, over, or behind; for specific idiomatic senses see individual entries get into, get over, etc.) To adopt, assume, arrive at, or progress towards (a certain position, location, state).
definitions.example: I'm getting into a muddle.

definitions.definition: To cover (a certain distance) while travelling.
definitions.example: to get a mile

definitions.definition: To begin (doing something or to do something).
definitions.example: After lunch we got chatting.

definitions.definition: To take or catch (a scheduled transportation service).
definitions.example: I normally get the 7:45 train.

definitions.definition: To respond to (a telephone call, a doorbell, etc).
definitions.example: Can you get that call, please? I'm busy.

definitions.definition: (followed by infinitive) To be able, be permitted, or have the opportunity (to do something desirable or ironically implied to be desirable).
definitions.example: Great. I get to clean the toilets today.

definitions.definition: To understand. (compare get it)
definitions.example: I don't get what you mean by "fun". This place sucks!

definitions.definition: To be told; be the recipient of (a question, comparison, opinion, etc.).
definitions.example: "You look just like Helen Mirren." / "I get that a lot."

definitions.definition: To be. Used to form the passive of verbs.
definitions.example: He got bitten by a dog.

definitions.definition: To become ill with or catch (a disease).
definitions.example: I went on holiday and got malaria.

definitions.definition: To catch out, trick successfully.
definitions.example: He keeps calling pretending to be my boss—it gets me every time.

definitions.definition: To perplex, stump.
definitions.example: That question's really got me.

definitions.definition: To find as an answer.
definitions.example: What did you get for question four?

definitions.definition: To bring to reckoning; to catch (as a criminal); to effect retribution.
definitions.example: I'm gonna get him for that.

definitions.definition: To hear completely; catch.
definitions.example: Sorry, I didn't get that. Could you repeat it?

definitions.definition: To getter.
definitions.example: I put the getter into the container to get the gases.

definitions.definition: To beget (of a father).
To learn; to commit to memory; to memorize; sometimes with out.
definitions.example: to get a lesson;  to get out one's Greek lesson

definitions.definition: Used with a personal pronoun to indicate that someone is being pretentious or grandiose.
definitions.example: Get her with her new hairdo.

definitions.definition: To go, to leave; to scram.
To kill.
definitions.example: They’re coming to get you, Barbara.

definitions.definition: To make acquisitions; to gain; to profit.
To measure.
definitions.example: Did you get her temperature?

definitions.definition: A water-borne vessel generally larger than a boat.
(chiefly in combination) A vessel which travels through any medium other than across land, such as an airship or spaceship.
A sailing vessel with three or more square-rigged masts.
A dish or utensil (originally fashioned like the hull of a ship) used to hold incense.
The third card of the Lenormand deck.
A group of vessels or vehicles.
Any group of associated items.
A large, coordinated group of people.
A number of vessels in company, especially war vessels; also, the collective naval force of a country, etc.
(British Royal Navy) Any command of vessels exceeding a squadron in size, or a rear admiral's command, composed of five sail-of-the-line, with any number of smaller vessels.
An arm of the sea; a run of water, such as an inlet or a creek.
A location, as on a navigable river, where barges are secured.
To float.
To pass over rapidly; to skim the surface of.

Floor; bottom; lower surface.
A house; home.

definitions.definition: The name of the Latin script letter A/a.
Disappearing, vanishing.
Barely there; almost imperceptible.
Ephemeral, fleeting, momentary.
A chemical hair treatment imparting or removing curliness, whose effects typically last for a period of weeks; a perm.

To perm (the hair).
Without end, eternal.

definitions.definition: Lasting for an indefinitely long time.

definitions.definition: (chiefly British) An area of land; a district, region.

A set region of land having particular human occupation or agreed limits, especially inhabited by members of the same race, speakers of the same language etc., or associated with a given person, occupation, species etc.
The territory of a nation, especially an independent nation state or formerly independent nation; a political entity asserting ultimate authority over a geographical area; a sovereign state.
(usually preceded by “the”) A rural area, as opposed to a town or city; the countryside.
The rock through which a vein runs.
The female genitalia, especially the vagina.
A style of popular music that originated in the folk music of the rural population of the southern and western United States and characterized by string-band instruments and simple melodies.
Something being indicated that is here; one of these.
Referring to the current context in a programming environment in C-like languages.
To the degree or extent indicated.
definitions.example: Do we need this many recommendations?

definitions.definition: The thing, item, etc. being indicated.
definitions.example: This isn't the item that I ordered.

definitions.definition: Indicates the speaker's strong approval or agreement with the previous material.

This isn't the item that I ordered.

definitions.definition: v	(now colloquial) Used in phrases with existential there (also here and where) when the semantic subject is plural.
An accepted (but deprecated and rarely used) SI unit of area equal to 100 square metres, or a former unit of approximately the same extent. Symbol: a.
(with "the") Human collective existence; existence in general.

definitions.definition: The Universe.

definitions.definition: A very large extent of country.
(speculation) A realm, such as planet, containing one or multiple societies of beings, especially intelligent ones.

definitions.definition: An individual or group perspective or social setting.

A subdivision of a game, consisting of a series of stages or levels that usually share a similar environment or theme.

definitions.definition: The twenty-second trump or major arcana card of the tarot.
A great amount.

definitions.definition: Age, era
To consider or cause to be considered from a global perspective; to consider as a global whole, rather than making or focussing on national or other distinctions; compare globalise.
To make real; to make worldly.

A trivial remark (especially in the term sweet nothings).
A nobody (insignificant person).

definitions.definition: Not at all; in no way.
Not any thing; no thing.
An absence of anything, including empty space, brightness, darkness, matter, or a vacuum.

definitions.definition: A condition; a set of circumstances applying at any given time.
High social standing or circumstance.
A polity.
(stochastic processes) An element of the range of the random variables that define a random process.
(grammar) The lexical aspect (aktionsart) of verbs or predicates that do not change over time.
To declare to be a fact.

definitions.definition: To make known.
definitions.example: State your intentions.

definitions.definition: Stately.

definitions.definition: To possess, own.
definitions.example: I have a house and a car.

definitions.definition: To hold, as something at someone's disposal.
definitions.example: Do you have the key? (not necessarily one's own key)

definitions.definition: Used to state the existence or presence of someone in a specified relationship with the subject.
definitions.example: I have a really mean boss.

definitions.definition: To partake of (a particular substance, especially food or drink, or action or activity).
definitions.example: Can I have a look at that?

definitions.definition: To be scheduled to attend, undertake or participate in.
definitions.example: Fred won't be able to come to the party; he has a meeting that day.

definitions.definition: To experience, go through, undergo.
definitions.example: He had surgery on his hip yesterday.

definitions.definition: To be afflicted with, suffer from.
definitions.example: He had a cold last week.

definitions.definition: (auxiliary verb, taking a past participle) Used in forming the perfect aspect.
definitions.example: I had already eaten.

definitions.definition: Used as an interrogative verb before a pronoun to form a tag question, echoing a previous use of 'have' as an auxiliary verb or, in certain cases, main verb. (For further discussion, see the appendix English tag questions.)
definitions.example: They haven't eaten dinner yet, have they?

definitions.definition: (auxiliary verb, taking a to-infinitive) See have to.
definitions.example: I have to go.

definitions.definition: To give birth to.
definitions.example: My mother had me when she was 25.

definitions.definition: To engage in sexual intercourse with.
definitions.example: He's always bragging about how many women he's had.

definitions.definition: To accept as a romantic partner.
definitions.example: Despite my protestations of love, she would not have me.

definitions.definition: (transitive with bare infinitive) To cause to, by a command, request or invitation.
definitions.example: They had me feed their dog while they were out of town.

definitions.definition: (transitive with adjective or adjective-phrase complement) To cause to be.
definitions.example: He had him arrested for trespassing.

definitions.definition: (transitive with bare infinitive) To be affected by an occurrence. (Used in supplying a topic that is not a verb argument.)
definitions.example: I've had three people today tell me my hair looks nice.

definitions.definition: (transitive with adjective or adjective-phrase complement) To depict as being.
definitions.example: Their stories differed; he said he'd been at work when the incident occurred, but her statement had him at home that entire evening.

definitions.definition: To defeat in a fight; take.
definitions.example: I could have him!

definitions.definition: (obsolete outside Ireland) To be able to speak (a language).
definitions.example: I have no German.

definitions.definition: To feel or be (especially painfully) aware of.
definitions.example: Dan certainly has arms today, probably from scraping paint off four columns the day before.

definitions.definition: To trick, to deceive.
definitions.example: You had me alright! I never would have thought that was just a joke.

definitions.definition: (often with present participle) To allow; to tolerate.
definitions.example: I asked my dad if I could go to the concert this Thursday, but he wouldn't have it since it's a school night.

definitions.definition: (often used in the negative) To believe, buy, be taken in by.
definitions.example: I made up an excuse as to why I was out so late, but my wife wasn't having any of it.

definitions.definition: To host someone; to take in as a guest.
definitions.example: Thank you for having me!

definitions.definition: To get a reading, measurement, or result from an instrument or calculation.
definitions.example: I have two contacts on my scope.

definitions.definition: (of a jury) To consider a court proceeding that has been completed; to begin deliberations on a case.
definitions.example: We'll schedule closing arguments for Thursday, and the jury will have the case by that afternoon.

definitions.definition: To make an observation of (a bird species).

A re-entrant angle; a nook or corner.
To enclose.
To take in; to harvest.
Located indoors, especially at home or at one's office or place of work.

definitions.definition: Located inside something.
definitions.example: Little by little I pushed the snake into the basket, until finally all of it was in.

definitions.definition: Inserted or fitted into something.

definitions.definition: Having been collected or received.

definitions.definition: In fashion; popular.

definitions.definition: Incoming.

definitions.definition: With privilege or possession; used to denote a holding, possession, or seisin.

definitions.definition: Currently batting.

definitions.definition: At or towards the interior of a defined space, such as a building or room.

definitions.definition: Towards the speaker or other reference point.

definitions.definition: After the beginning of something.

definitions.definition: (in combination, after a verb) Denotes a gathering of people assembled for the stated activity, sometimes, though not always, suggesting a protest.

Into.

definitions.definition: To host someone; to take in as a guest.

definitions.definition: (of a jury) To consider a court proceeding that has been completed; to begin deliberations on a case.
definitions.example: We'll schedule closing arguments for Thursday, and the jury will have the case by that afternoon.

definitions.definition: A command.
A request for some product or service; a commission to purchase, sell, or supply goods.
A group of religious adherents, especially monks or nuns, set apart within their religion by adherence to a particular rule or set of principles.
definitions.example: St. Ignatius Loyola founded the Jesuit order in 1537.

definitions.definition: An association of knights.
definitions.example: the Order of the Garter, the Order of the Bath.

definitions.definition: Any group of people with common interests.
A decoration, awarded by a government, a dynastic house, or a religious body to an individual, usually for distinguished service to a nation or to humanity.
A rank in the classification of organisms, below class and above family; a taxon at that rank.
definitions.example: Magnolias belong to the order Magnoliales.

definitions.definition: A number of things or persons arranged in a fixed or suitable place, or relative position; a rank; a row; a grade; especially, a rank or class in society; a distinct character, kind, or sort.
definitions.example: talent of a high order

definitions.definition: (chiefly plural) An ecclesiastical grade or rank, as of deacon, priest, or bishop; the office of the Christian ministry.
definitions.example: to take orders, or to take holy orders, that is, to enter some grade of the ministry

definitions.definition: The disposition of a column and its component parts, and of the entablature resting upon it, in classical architecture; hence (since the column and entablature are the characteristic features of classical architecture) a style or manner of architectural design.
The sequence in which a side’s batsmen bat; the batting order.
A power of polynomial function in an electronic circuit’s block, such as a filter, an amplifier, etc.
definitions.example: a 3-stage cascade of a 2nd-order bandpass Butterworth filter

definitions.definition: The overall power of the rate law of a chemical reaction, expressed as a polynomial function of concentrations of reactants and products.
The cardinality, or number of elements in a set, group, or other structure regardable as a set.

(of an element of a group) For given group G and element g ∈ G, the smallest positive natural number n, if it exists, such that (using multiplicative notation), gn = e, where e is the identity element of G; if no such number exists, the element is said to be of infinite order (or sometimes zero order).
The number of vertices in a graph.
A partially ordered set.
The relation on a partially ordered set that determines that it is, in fact, a partially ordered set.
The sum of the exponents on the variables in a monomial, or the highest such among all monomials in a polynomial.
definitions.example: A quadratic polynomial, a x^2 + b x + c, is said to be of order (or degree) 2.

definitions.definition: A written direction to furnish someone with money or property; compare money order, postal order.
To set in some sort of order.
To arrange, set in proper order.
To issue a command to.
definitions.example: He ordered me to leave.

definitions.definition: To request some product or service; to secure by placing an order.
definitions.example: to order groceries

definitions.definition: To admit to holy orders; to ordain; to receive into the ranks of the ministry.

definitions.definition: A means of exit, escape, reprieve, etc.
definitions.example: They wrote the law to give those organizations an out.

definitions.definition: A state in which a member of the batting team is removed from play due to the application of various rules of the game such as striking out, hitting a fly ball which is caught by the fielding team before bouncing, etc.

A dismissal; a state in which a member of the batting team finishes his turn at bat, due to the application of various rules of the game, such as the bowler knocking over the batsman's wicket with the ball.
A card which can make a hand a winner.
A trip out; an outing.
(chiefly in the plural) One who, or that which, is out; especially, one who is out of office.
A place or space outside of something; a nook or corner; an angle projecting outward; an open space.
A word or words omitted by the compositor in setting up copy; an omission.
To eject; to expel.
To reveal (a person) as LGBT+ (gay, trans, etc).
To reveal (a person or organization) as having a certain secret, such as a being a secret agent or undercover detective.
To reveal (a secret).
definitions.example: A Brazilian company outed the new mobile phone design.

definitions.definition: To come or go out; to get out or away; to become public or apparent.
Not at home; not at one's office or place of employment.
definitions.example: I'm sorry, Mr Smith is out at the moment.

definitions.definition: Not inside or within something.
definitions.example: I worked away cleaning the U-bend until all the gunge was out.

definitions.definition: Freed from confinement or secrecy.
definitions.example: My secret is out.

definitions.definition: Not fitted or inserted into something.
definitions.example: The TV won't work with the plug out!

definitions.definition: Of the ball or other playing implement, falling or passing outside the bounds of the playing area.
definitions.example: I thought the ball hit the line, but the umpire said it was out.

definitions.definition: Released, available for purchase, download or other use.
definitions.example: Did you hear? Their newest CD is out!

definitions.definition: (in various games; used especially of a batsman or batter in cricket or baseball) Dismissed from play under the rules of the game.
definitions.example: He bowls, Johnson pokes at it ... and ... Johnson is out! Caught behind by Ponsonby!

definitions.definition: Openly acknowledging that one is LGBT+ (gay, trans, etc).
definitions.example: It's no big deal to be out in the entertainment business.

definitions.definition: (by extension) Open, public; public about or openly acknowledging some (usually specified) identity.
(of flowers) In bloom.
definitions.example: The garden looks beautiful now that the roses are out.

definitions.definition: (of the sun, moon or stars) Visible in the sky; not obscured by clouds.
definitions.example: The sun is out, and it's a lovely day.

definitions.definition: (of lamps, fires etc.) Not shining or burning.
definitions.example: I called round to the house but all the lights were out and no one was home.

definitions.definition: (of ideas, plans, etc.) Discarded; no longer a possibility.
definitions.example: Right, so that idea's out. Let's move on to the next one.

definitions.definition: (of certain services, devices, or facilities) Not available; out of service.
definitions.example: My wi-fi is out.

definitions.definition: (of a user of a service) Not having availability of a service, as power or communications.
definitions.example: Most of the city got service back yesterday, but my neighborhood is still out.

definitions.definition: (of an organization, etc.) Temporarily not in operation, or not being attended as usual.
definitions.example: when school gets out for today, when college is out for the summer

definitions.definition: Of the tide, at or near its lowest level.
definitions.example: You can walk to the island when the tide's out.

definitions.definition: No longer popular or in fashion.
definitions.example: Black is out this season. The new black is white.

definitions.definition: Without; no longer in possession of; not having more
definitions.example: Do you have any bread? Sorry, we're out.

definitions.definition: (of calculations or measurements) Containing errors or discrepancies; in error by a stated amount.
definitions.example: Nothing adds up in this report. All these figures are out.

definitions.definition: Of a young lady: having entered society and available to be courted.
Away from the inside, centre or other point of reference.
definitions.example: For six hours the tide flows out, then for six hours it flows in.

definitions.definition: Away from home or one's usual place.
definitions.example: Let's eat out tonight

definitions.definition: Outside; not indoors.
definitions.example: Last night we slept out under the stars.

definitions.definition: Away from; at a distance.
definitions.example: Keep out!

definitions.definition: Into a state of non-operation; into non-existence.
definitions.example: I painted out that nasty mark on the wall.

definitions.definition: To the end; completely.
definitions.example: I haven't finished. Hear me out.

definitions.definition: Used to intensify or emphasize.
definitions.example: The place was all decked out for the holidays.

definitions.definition: (of the sun, moon, stars, etc.) So as to be visible in the sky, and not covered by clouds, fog, etc.
definitions.example: The sun came out after the rain, and we saw a rainbow.

definitions.definition: Of a player, so as to be disqualified from playing further by some action of a member of the opposing team (such as being stumped in cricket).
definitions.example: Wilson was bowled out for five runs.

definitions.definition: From from the inside to the outside of; out of.
(procedure word) A radio procedure word meaning that the station is finished with its transmission and does not expect a response.
definitions.example: Destruction. Two T-72s destroyed. Three foot mobiles down. Out.

definitions.definition: Get out; begone; away!

definitions.definition: The day immediately before today; one day ago.
definitions.example: Today is the child of yesterday and the parent of tomorrow.

definitions.definition: The recent past, often disparaging.
definitions.example: yesterday's technology

definitions.definition: On the day before today.
definitions.example: I started to watch the video yesterday, but could only finish it this evening.

definitions.definition: As soon as possible.
definitions.example: I want this done yesterday!

yesterday's technology

definitions.definition: An uncertainty.
Modifies a verb, indicating a lack of certainty.
definitions.example: Perhaps John will come over for dinner.

definitions.definition: By chance.

examples: Perhaps John will come over for dinner.

definitions.definition: (ditransitive) To obtain; to acquire.
definitions.example: I'm going to get a computer tomorrow from the discount store.

definitions.definition: To receive.
definitions.example: He got a severe reprimand for that.

definitions.definition: (in a perfect construction, with present-tense meaning) To have. See usage notes.
definitions.example: I've got a concert ticket for you.

definitions.definition: To fetch, bring, take.
definitions.example: Can you get my bag from the living-room, please?

definitions.definition: To become, or cause oneself to become.
definitions.example: I'm getting hungry; how about you?

definitions.definition: To cause to become; to bring about.
definitions.example: I can't get these boots off (or on).

definitions.definition: To cause to do.
definitions.example: I can't get it to work.

definitions.definition: To cause to come or go or move.
definitions.example: I got him to his room.

definitions.definition: To cause to be in a certain status or position.
definitions.example: Get him here at once.

definitions.definition: (with various prepositions, such as into, over, or behind; for specific idiomatic senses see individual entries get into, get over, etc.) To adopt, assume, arrive at, or progress towards (a certain position, location, state).
definitions.example: I'm getting into a muddle.

definitions.definition: To cover (a certain distance) while travelling.
definitions.example: to get a mile

definitions.definition: To begin (doing something or to do something).
definitions.example: After lunch we got chatting.

definitions.definition: To take or catch (a scheduled transportation service).
definitions.example: I normally get the 7:45 train.

definitions.definition: To respond to (a telephone call, a doorbell, etc).
definitions.example: Can you get that call, please? I'm busy.

definitions.definition: (followed by infinitive) To be able, be permitted, or have the opportunity (to do something desirable or ironically implied to be desirable).
definitions.example: Great. I get to clean the toilets today.

definitions.definition: To understand. (compare get it)
definitions.example: I don't get what you mean by "fun". This place sucks!

definitions.definition: To be told; be the recipient of (a question, comparison, opinion, etc.).
definitions.example: "You look just like Helen Mirren." / "I get that a lot."

definitions.definition: To be. Used to form the passive of verbs.
definitions.example: He got bitten by a dog.

definitions.definition: To become ill with or catch (a disease).
definitions.example: I went on holiday and got malaria.

definitions.definition: To catch out, trick successfully.
definitions.example: He keeps calling pretending to be my boss—it gets me every time.

definitions.definition: To perplex, stump.
definitions.example: That question's really got me.

definitions.definition: To find as an answer.
definitions.example: What did you get for question four?

definitions.definition: To bring to reckoning; to catch (as a criminal); to effect retribution.
definitions.example: I'm gonna get him for that.

definitions.definition: To hear completely; catch.
definitions.example: Sorry, I didn't get that. Could you repeat it?

definitions.definition: To getter.
definitions.example: I put the getter into the container to get the gases.

definitions.definition: To beget (of a father).
To learn; to commit to memory; to memorize; sometimes with out.
definitions.example: to get a lesson;  to get out one's Greek lesson

definitions.definition: Used with a personal pronoun to indicate that someone is being pretentious or grandiose.
definitions.example: Get her with her new hairdo.

definitions.definition: To go, to leave; to scram.
To kill.
definitions.example: They’re coming to get you, Barbara.

definitions.definition: To make acquisitions; to gain; to profit.
To measure.
definitions.example: Did you get her temperature?

definitions.example: In other areas, glacier loss creates serious risk of a dry period across the Third Pole, Wang said.

definitions.definition: The destruction or ruin of an object.
Something that has been destroyed or ruined.
definitions.example: It was a terrible crash; both cars were total losses.

definitions.definition: Defeat; an instance of being defeated.
definitions.example: The match ended in their first loss of the season.

definitions.definition: The death of a person or animal.
definitions.example: The battle was won, but losses were great.

definitions.definition: The condition of grief caused by losing someone or something, especially someone who has died.
definitions.example: Her daughter's sense of loss eventually led to depression.

definitions.definition: (financial) The sum an entity loses on balance.
definitions.example: The sum of expenditures and taxes minus total income is a loss, when this difference is positive.

definitions.definition: Electricity of kinetic power expended without doing useful work.
definitions.example: The inefficiency of many old-fashioned power plants exceeds 60% loss before the subsequent losses during transport over the grid.

definitions.definition: To change place.
To change in state or status
To move through time.
To be accepted.
In any game, to decline to play in one's turn.
To do or be better.
To take heed.
The period of time that has already happened, in contrast to the present and the future.
definitions.example: a book about a time machine that can transport people back into the past

definitions.definition: (grammar) The past tense.
Having already happened; in the past; finished.
definitions.example: past glories

definitions.definition: (postmodifier) Following expressions of time to indicate how long ago something happened; ago.
Of a period of time: having just gone by; previous.
definitions.example: during the past year

definitions.definition: (grammar) Of a tense, expressing action that has already happened or a previously-existing state.
definitions.example: past tense

definitions.definition: In a direction that passes.

definitions.definition: Passing by, especially without stopping or being delayed.

definitions.definition: Beyond in place, quantity or time.

definitions.definition: No longer capable of.
definitions.example: I'm past caring what he thinks of me.

definitions.definition: Having recovered or moved on from (a traumatic experience, etc.).

definitions.definition: v	As an auxiliary verb:
The person or thing in the third position.
definitions.example: Jones came in third.

definitions.definition: One of three equal parts of a whole.
definitions.example: He ate a third of the pie. Divided by two-thirds.

definitions.definition: The third gear of a gearbox.
definitions.example: Now put it into third.

definitions.definition: An interval consisting of the first and third notes in a scale.
definitions.example: They sing in thirds.

definitions.definition: Third base
definitions.example: The play ended with Jones standing on third.

definitions.definition: A handicap of one stroke every third hole.
A third-class degree, awarded to the lowest achievers in an honours degree programme
One sixtieth of a second, i.e., the third in a series of fractional parts in a sexagesimal number system. Also formerly known as a tierce.
To agree with a proposition or statement after it has already been seconded.
To divide into three equal parts.
The ordinal form of the cardinal number three; Coming after the second.
definitions.example: The third tree from the left is my favorite.

examples: Jones came in third.
He ate a third of the pie. Divided by two-thirds.
Now put it into third.
They sing in thirds.
The play ended with Jones standing on third.
The third tree from the left is my favorite.

definitions.definition: (physical) To remove a gap.
(social) To finish, to terminate.
To come or gather around; to enclose; to encompass; to confine.
To have a vector sum of 0; that is, to form a closed polygon.
Sealed, made inaccessible or impassable; not open.
(of a store or business) Not operating or conducting trade.
Not public.
definitions.example: closed source  a closed committee

definitions.definition: (of a set) Having an open complement.
(of a set) Such that its image under the specified operation is contained in it.

definitions.definition: (of a formula) Lacking a free variable.
(of a walk) Whose first and last vertices are the same, forming a closed loop.
Formed by closing the mouth and nose passages completely, like the consonants /t/, /d/ and /p/.
Having the sound cut off sharply by a following consonant, like the /ɪ/ in pin.

definitions.definition: The process of developing; growth, directed change.
definitions.example: The development of this story has been slow.

definitions.definition: The process by which a mature multicellular organism or part of an organism is produced by the addition of new cells.
definitions.example: The organism has reached a crucial stage in its development.

definitions.definition: Something which has developed.
definitions.example: Our news team brings you the latest developments.

definitions.definition: A project consisting of one or more commercial or residential buildings.
The building of such a project.
The application of new ideas to practical problems (cf. research).
definitions.example: Our development department has produced three new adhesives this year.

definitions.definition: The active placement of the pieces, or the process of achieving it.
definitions.example: White's development is good, but black's has been hampered by the pawn on e5.

definitions.definition: The process by in which previous material is transformed and restated.
The second section of a piece of music in sonata form, in which the original theme is revisited in altered and varying form.
The expression of a function in the form of a series.
A group of building complexes or apartments. Often used for low income housing.

definitions.definition: (Singlish) Used to contradict an underlying assumption held by the interlocutor.
Something; thing; stuff.
The identity of a thing, as an answer to a question of what.
Something that is addressed by what, as opposed to a person, addressed by who.
(usually followed by "with," but also sometimes "would" or "might," especially in finance) In some manner or degree; in part; partly. See also what with

definitions.definition: Such.
definitions.example: What a beautiful day!

definitions.definition: Why.

(interrogative) Which thing, event, circumstance, etc.: used interrogatively in asking for the specification of an identity, quantity, quality, etc.
That which; those that; the thing that.

Whatever.

definitions.definition: To attend.

definitions.definition: To come to (a certain condition or state).

definitions.definition: To turn out, to result; to come to (a certain result).

definitions.definition: To tend (toward a result).

definitions.definition: To contribute to a (specified) end product or result.

definitions.definition: To pass, to be used up:
To die.
To be discarded.

definitions.definition: To be lost or out:
To break down or apart:
To be sold.
definitions.example: Everything must go.

definitions.definition: To be given, especially to be assigned or allotted.
definitions.example: The award went to Steven Spielberg.

definitions.definition: To survive or get by; to last or persist for a stated length of time.
definitions.example: Can you two go twenty minutes without arguing?!

definitions.definition: To have a certain record.
definitions.example: The team is going five in a row.

definitions.definition: To be authoritative, accepted, or valid:
To say (something), to make a sound:
To be expressed or composed (a certain way).

definitions.definition: To resort (to).

definitions.definition: To apply or subject oneself to:

definitions.example: The water is so cold! — That it is.

definitions.definition: (relative) (plural that) Which, who; representing a subject, direct object, indirect object, or object of a preposition.
definitions.example: The CPR course that she took really came in handy.

definitions.definition: Used in place of relative adverbs such as where or when; often omitted.
definitions.example: the last time that [= when] I went to Europe

definitions.definition: Introducing a clause which is the subject or object of a verb (such as one involving reported speech), or which is a complement to a previous statement.
definitions.example: He told me that the book is a good read.

definitions.definition: Introducing a subordinate clause expressing a reason or cause: because, in that.
definitions.example: Be glad that you have enough to eat.

definitions.definition: Introducing a subordinate clause that expresses an aim, purpose or goal ("final"), and usually contains the auxiliaries may, might or should: so, so that.
Introducing — especially, but not exclusively, with an antecedent like so or such — a subordinate clause expressing a result, consequence or effect.
definitions.example: The noise was so loud that she woke up.

definitions.definition: Introducing a premise or supposition for consideration: seeing as; inasmuch as; given that; as would appear from the fact that.
Introducing a subordinate clause modifying an adverb.
definitions.example: How often did she visit him? — Twice that I saw.

definitions.definition: Introducing an exclamation expressing a desire or wish.
definitions.example: Oh that spring would come!

definitions.definition: Introducing an exclamation expressing a strong emotion such as sadness or surprise.

examples: "The ribbon was that thin." "I disagree, I say it was not that thin, it was thicker... or maybe thinner..."

The CPR course that she took really came in handy.

Be glad that you have enough to eat.
The noise was so loud that she woke up.

definitions.definition: The time at which something happens.
definitions.example: A good article will cover the who, the what, the when, the where, the why and the how.

definitions.definition: (interrogative) At what time? At which time? Upon which occasion or circumstance? Used to introduce direct or indirect questions about time.
definitions.example: Do you know when they arrived?

definitions.definition: At an earlier time and under different, usually less favorable, circumstances.
definitions.example: He's mister high and mighty now, but I remember him when.

definitions.definition: (relative) At which, on which, during which: often omitted or replaced with that.
definitions.example: That was the day when the Twin Towers fell.

definitions.definition: (interrogative) What time; which time.
definitions.example: Since when do I need your permission?

definitions.definition: The time that.
definitions.example: I recall when they were called the Greys.

definitions.definition: At (or as soon as) that time that; at the (or any and every) time that; if.
definitions.example: A player wins when [as soon as, or at any time that, if] she has four cards of the same suit.

definitions.definition: During the time that; at the time of the action of the following clause or participle phrase.
definitions.example: Be careful when crossing the street.

definitions.definition: At what time; at which time.
definitions.example: I am here till Friday, when [i.e. at which time] I leave for Senegal.

definitions.definition: Since; given the fact that; considering that.
definitions.example: I don't see the point of putting up Christmas decorations when I am the only person who is going to see them.

definitions.definition: Whereas; although; at the same time as; in spite of the fact that.
definitions.example: He keeps changing things when the existing system works perfectly well.

definitions.definition: That's enough, a command to stop adding something, especially an ingredient of food or drink.
Expressing impatience. (Compare what.)

definitions.definition: (gerund) The act of persons or things that meet.
definitions.example: Meeting him will be exciting. I enjoy meeting new people.

definitions.definition: A gathering of persons for a purpose; an assembly.
definitions.example: We need to have a meeting about that soon.

definitions.definition: (collective) The people at such a gathering.
definitions.example: What has the meeting decided.

definitions.definition: An encounter between people, even accidental.
definitions.example: They came together in a chance meeting on the way home from work.

definitions.definition: A place or instance of junction or intersection; a confluence.
definitions.example: Earthquakes occur at the meeting of tectonic plates.

definitions.definition: A religious service held by a charismatic preacher in small towns in the United States.
An administrative unit in the Religious Society of Friends (Quakers).
definitions.example: Denver meeting is a part of Intermountain yearly meeting.

definitions.definition: An act of thinking; consideration (of something).
definitions.example: I'll have a think about that and let you know.

definitions.definition: To ponder, to go over in one's head.
definitions.example: Idly, the detective thought what his next move should be.

definitions.definition: To communicate to oneself in one's mind, to try to find a solution to a problem.
definitions.example: I thought for three hours about the problem and still couldn’t find the solution.

definitions.definition: To conceive of something or someone (usually followed by of; infrequently, by on).
definitions.example: I tend to think of her as rather ugly.

definitions.definition: To be of opinion (that); to consider, judge, regard, or look upon (something) as.
definitions.example: At the time I thought his adamant refusal to give in right.

definitions.definition: To guess; to reckon.
definitions.example: I think she’ll pass the examination.

definitions.definition: To plan; to be considering; to be of a mind (to do something).
To presume; to venture.

I thought for three hours about the problem and still couldn’t find the solution.
I tend to think of her as rather ugly.

I think she’ll pass the examination.

definitions.definition: Frequent.
Frequently, many times.
definitions.example: I often walk to work when the weather is nice.

examples: I often walk to work when the weather is nice.

definitions.definition: A drawing showing technical details of a building, machine, etc., with unwanted details omitted, and often using symbols rather than detailed drawing to represent doors, valves, etc.
definitions.example: The plans for many important buildings were once publicly available.

definitions.definition: A set of intended actions, usually mutually related, through which one expects to achieve a goal.
definitions.example: He didn't really have a plan; he had a goal and a habit of control.

definitions.definition: A two-dimensional drawing of a building as seen from above with obscuring or irrelevant details such as roof removed, or of a floor of a building, revealing the internal layout; as distinct from the elevation.
definitions.example: Seen in plan, the building had numerous passageways not apparent to visitors.

definitions.definition: A method; a way of procedure; a custom.
A subscription to a service.
definitions.example: a phone plan

definitions.definition: To design (a building, machine, etc.).
definitions.example: The architect planned the building for the client.

definitions.definition: To create a plan for.
definitions.example: They jointly planned the project in phases, with good detail for the first month.

definitions.definition: To intend.
definitions.example: He planned to go, but work intervened.

definitions.definition: To make a plan.
definitions.example: They planned for the worst, bringing lots of emergency supplies.

definitions.definition: As the direct object of a verb.
definitions.example: Can you hear me?

definitions.definition: Myself; as a reflexive direct object of a verb.
As the object of a preposition.
definitions.example: Come with me.

definitions.definition: As the indirect object of a verb.
definitions.example: He gave me this.

definitions.definition: Myself; as a reflexive indirect object of a verb; the ethical dative.
As the complement of the copula (be or is).
definitions.example: It wasn't me.

definitions.definition: (with and) As the subject of a verb.
definitions.example: Me and my friends played a game.

definitions.definition: (not with and) As the subject of a verb.
